				posted 2004-08-25 21:17&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;
				<A href="edit.php?board=player&id=8918"><IMG alt="Edit/Delete Message" src="http://www.archspace.org/image/forum/edit.gif" border=0></A> 
			    <A href="reply.php?board=player&id=8906"><IMG alt="Reply w/Quote" src="http://www.archspace.org/image/forum/quote.gif" border=0></A>
			    <HR color=#000000 SIZE=-1>
			  	1) Decreased attack range would help, but not solve the problem.  I think that 80%/125% would be a good compromise between the number of targets available and being able to easily stomp your target into the ground.  Keep in mind that a tighter range makes allied fleets more influential.<br />
<br />
2) Actually the weaker planets are better for the game because the difference between a council that harvests all URs and a council that has only Normals isn't as bad as it was before.  This has been a great tool for leveling the playing field.  It does cut down on how quickly the dominant council builds up, but the lower councils build up the same and better with the new increase in poor and ultra poor planets.<br />
<br />
3) Blockading should be reserved for war.  This kind of an attack is necessary (attack ships but not gain planet), but not outside of war.  However, because a lot of information can be gained with a blockade (planet information, # of fleets, etc.) even if you cancel on the last screen sending your gunboat into sortie, it is necessary to have some kind of Recon mission take it's place so that method of gathering information is still available (fleets automatically sortie afterwards and never engage the enemy).  I'm not how much this would help the situation though.			   <P align=right></P>
