				posted 2004-08-26 03:20&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;
				<A href="edit.php?board=player&id=8956"><IMG alt="Edit/Delete Message" src="http://www.archspace.org/image/forum/edit.gif" border=0></A> 
			    <A href="reply.php?board=player&id=8906"><IMG alt="Reply w/Quote" src="http://www.archspace.org/image/forum/quote.gif" border=0></A>
			    <HR color=#000000 SIZE=-1>
			  	It's always been a single council dominating the game, or two coalitions of large councils - in Archspace, the people with the most powerful fleets always win. <br />
<br />
A couple possible ideas to reduce the phenomena of single-council dominance:<br />
1. Reduce attack ranges. I've been saying 75%-133% for a long time, but many people don't like the idea because it means less planets they can steal.<br />
2. More aggressive councils. In AS, the aggressive councils always win - its the reason the Koreans, Azguard, TE, etc dominates. They build up a good start, and nobody can catch up with them. Problem is, if players aren't aggressive, then there's not much else we can do to rectify that. Perhaps some way of giving attackers a bonus so that people will try to defend less.<br />
3. Stop mega-councils. I realize this is probably a pretty unpopular thing to say, but dominating the entire game with only one single council will be much harder than doing it with many more councils and players.<br />
4. At the beginning of the reset, let players choose their council, but then don't let them apply to other councils. At the end of each round, let them stay with their council or find a new one. This allows you to be with your friends, but stops the hop-rape-jump routine.			   <P align=right></P>
			</TD>
		  </TR>

		
